We present disc--wind--magnetosphere hybrid radiative transfer models for
 classical T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars, and investigate the formation of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 to understand their complex circumstellar environment, and to understand
 the wide variety of emission line profiles seen in observations.
 To overcome the limited applicability of the radiative transfer models
 with only magnetospherical accretion to fitting observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles, and to any other lines affected by the stellar wind) presented,
 two types of kinematic wind models are introduced: (1)\SpecialChar ~
the bipolar wind
 model in which the wind is originated from the star itself, and (2)\SpecialChar ~
the
 disc-wind model in which the wind originates from the inner part of the
 accretion disc.
 We perform systematic investigations of the model parameters for the wind
 and the magnetosphere to search for possible geometrical and physical condition
s which lead to the types of the profiles seen in observations.
 We find both wind models can reproduce the wide range profile types seen
 is observations.
 We also find the inclination dependency of the line equivalent width predicted
 by the bipolar wind model agree with trends seen in the observation, but
 the disc-wind model does not.
 Using the model results, we examine the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 spectroscopic classification used by Reipurth et.\SpecialChar ~
al , and discuss the basic
 physical conditions required to reproduce the profiles in each classified
 type.
 Using the hybrid model, we fit the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 from the optical component of T\SpecialChar ~
Tau triple system (T\SpecialChar ~
Tau\SpecialChar ~
N), and find its
 ratio of the mass-loss to mass-accretion rate to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.18$
\end_inset 

 with the cold (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}\approx8000\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

) bipolar wind model .
