\layout Subsection

Magnetosphere
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Magnetosphere}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We adopt the magnetospherical accretion flow model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

, as done so by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

 and by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

, in which the gas accretion on to the stellar surface from the innermost
 part of the accretion disc occurs through a dipolar stellar magnetic field.
 The magnetic field is assumed to be so strong that the gas flow does not
 affect the underlying magnetic field itself.
 As shown in Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

, the innermost radius (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

) of the magnetosphere at the equatorial plane (
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset 

) is assigned to be same as the inner radius (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{di}}$
\end_inset 

) of the accretion disc where the flow is truncated.
 In our models, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

 and the outer radius (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

) of the magnetosphere (at the equatorial plane) are set to be 
\begin_inset Formula $2.2\, R_{\sun}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3.0\, R_{\sun}$
\end_inset 

 respectively.
 The former value corresponds to the co-rotation radius of the accretion
 disc, and the geometry of the magnetic field/stream lines is kept constant
 throughout this paper.
 The geometry of the magnetosphere is identical to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

small/wide
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The magnetic field and the gas stream lines are assumed to have the following
 simple form: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r=R_{\mathrm{m}}\sin^{2}\theta\label{eq:dipole}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep[see][]{ghosh:1977}
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

 are coordinates of the field point (
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

) in Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

 in spherical coordinates, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset 

is the radial distance to the field line at the equatorial plane (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/2$
\end_inset 

).
 The range of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset 

is restricted between 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

.
 Using the field geometry above and the conservation of energy, the velocity
 and the density of the accreting gas along the steam line are found as
 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The temperature structure of the magnetospheric used by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

 is simply adopted here.
 They computed the temperature assuming a volumetric heating rate which
 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-3}$
\end_inset 

, and using the energy balance of the radiative cooling rate of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1982}
\end_inset 

 and the heating rate 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

.
 Although the temperature structure of the accretion steam could significantly
 affect the line source function, for the purpose of the exploring the general
 characteristics of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 formation, this simple form is a reasonable assumption.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{martin:1996}
\end_inset 

 presented the self-consistent determination of the thermal structure of
 the in-flowing gas along the dipole magnetic field (equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dipole}

\end_inset 

) by solving the heat equation couple to rate equations for hydrogen.
 He found that main heat source is adiabatic compression due to the converging
 nature of the flow, and the major contributors of the cooling process are
 bremsstrahlung radiation and line emission from Ca\SpecialChar ~
II and Mg\SpecialChar ~
II ions.
 The results of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{martin:1996}
\end_inset 

 qualitatively agrees with that of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Subsection

Bipolar Wind
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:wind_jet}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

As mentioned earlier, the wind model presented here is to simulate the collimate
d MHD disc-wind model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 in large scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim100$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU) , and the alternative wind model which resembles the model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 in small scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU) will be presented later (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Alternative-model-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

Similar to the simple wind model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

, the following parametrisation of collimated bipolar wind (region 3 in
 Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

) is adopted.
 The wind velocity field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{\mathrm{wind}}\left(r,\theta\right)$
\end_inset 

, is consist of radial and azimuthal components which depend on the spherical
 coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

.
 The radial component 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset 

 is assumed to be in the classical beta-velocity law 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep[c.f.][]{castor:1979}
\end_inset 

, and the azimuthal component 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 is assumed to be a constant fraction (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

) of the Keplerian velocity for a given distance (
\begin_inset Formula $w=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}$
\end_inset 

) from the symmetry axis (
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

-axis) , i.e.:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\mathbf{v}_{\mathrm{wind}} & = & v_{r}\hat{\mathbf{r}}+v_{\phi}\hat{\mathbf{\bphi}}\label{eq:wind_velocity_def}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{r}\left(r\right)=v_{r0}+\left(v_{\infty}-v_{r0}\right)\left(1-\frac{R_{\mathrm{mo}}}{r}\right)^{\beta}\,,\label{eq:wind_velocity_radial_part}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{\phi}\left(w\right)=\gamma\,\left(\frac{GM_{*}}{w}\right)^{1/2}\,,\label{eq:wind_velocity_azimuth_part}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Note that the base of the wind starts at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

.
 This is chosen so mainly for computational simplicity i.e.
 to avoid the overlap between the wind and the magnetosphere; however, see
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{matt:2005}
\end_inset 

 for the possibility that wind originates from the stellar surface (restricted
 near the polar caps).
 The range of the polar angle for the wind is restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>\left|\theta_{\mathrm{disc}}\right|$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{disc}}$
\end_inset 

 is the opening angle of the accretion disc, to avoid the overlap.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r0}$
\end_inset 

is the small radial velocity at the base of the wind (
\begin_inset Formula $r=R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

).
 Normally, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r0}=10\,\mathrm{km\, s^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 which is approximately equal to the thermal velocity of hydrogen with 
\begin_inset Formula $T=7500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

.
 Following 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0.05$
\end_inset 

 is adopted.
 The dependency of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset 

 in polar direction (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset 

) on the values of wind acceleration parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 is shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:wind_vr_rho}

\end_inset 

.
 All other parameters describing the wind are fixed as the standard values
 given in Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Further, the density of the wind is assumed to be axi-symmetric and separable
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

 for computational simplicity, i.e., 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho\left(r,\theta\right)=P\left(r\right)\, F\left(\theta\right)\label{eq:wind_density_def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F\left(\theta\right)=n\,\cos^{b}\theta\label{eq:wind_density_theta}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

 is normally positive even number (for the density symmetric about the equatoria
l plane), and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 is the angular normalisation constant.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset 

, the wind is spherically symmetric except for the parts disrupted by the
 accretion disc.
 The larger the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

, the higher the degree of the collimation.
 By integrating equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:wind_density_theta}

\end_inset 

 over angles and normalising the integral to 
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi$
\end_inset 

, one finds 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n=\frac{1+b}{1-\cos^{1+b}\theta_{\mathrm{wind}}}\,.\label{eq:wind_density_theta_norm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Assuming the total mass-loss rate by the wind/jet is 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 and the mass-flux conserves in time, the radial part of the density function
 is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(r\right)=\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}\,\left[4\pi r^{2}v_{r}\left(r\right)\right]^{-1}$
\end_inset 

; hence, Equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:wind_density_def}

\end_inset 

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho\left(r,\theta\right)=\frac{n\,\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}\,\cos^{b}\theta}{4\pi r^{2}\, v_{r}\left(r\right)}\,.\label{eq:wind_density_final}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 For a given mass-accretion rate, the wind mass-loss rate in our typical
 model is assigned from the ratio of mass-loss to mass-accretion rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}/\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}\approx0.1$
\end_inset 

), indicated by both observations and MHD calculations (e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koenigl:2000}
\end_inset 

).
 Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:wind_vr_rho}

\end_inset 

 shows the density along a streamline in the polar direction (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset 

), for different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 with all other parameters fixed as the standard values (Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

).
 The density is relatively sensitive to the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r<10\, R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

, but a little difference is seen beyond 
\begin_inset Formula $r<100\, R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

.
 
