\layout Standard

We have extended the TORUS radiative transfer code (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{harries:2000}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kurosawa:2004a}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

) to compute the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles from pre-main-sequence stars which are surrounded by one or more
 of the followings: the magnetospherical accretion flow, the out-flowing
 collimated wind, and the accretion disc.
 Previously in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

, the model used in the three-dimensional (3-D) adaptive mesh refinement
 (AMR) to investigate the line variability mainly associated with rotational
 motion of complex geometrical configurations of magnetospherical flow (see
 also 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt*{kurosawa:2005a}
\end_inset 

).
 We modified the code to handle the two-dimensional (2-D) density distribution,
 and restricted our models to be axi-symmetric.
 It was done so in order to enable us to explore rather large number of
 parameter spaces (c.f.\SpecialChar ~
section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:model-configuration}

\end_inset 

).
 Note that the velocity field is still in 3-D -- the third component can
 be calculated by using the symmetry for a given value of azimuthal angle.
 The examples of how the AMR grid for the purpose of the radiative transfer
 is constructed are presented in e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{wolf:1999}
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{kurosawa:2001a}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{steinacker:2003} 
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The computation of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 is divided in two parts: (1)\SpecialChar ~
the source function calculation (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) and (2)\SpecialChar ~
the observed flux/profile calculation.
 In the first process, we have utilised the method by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{klein:1978}
\end_inset 

 (see also 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{rybicki:1978}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

) in which the Sobolev approximation method is applied.
 The population of the bound states of hydrogen are assumed to be in statistical
 equilibrium, and the gas to be in radiative equilibrium.
 Our hydrogen atom model consist of 14 bound state and continuum.
 Readers are refer to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{klein:1978}
\end_inset 

 for details.
 
\layout Standard

To compute the observed line profile, the Monte Carlo radiative transfer
 method (e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{hillier:1991}
\end_inset 

) using the Sobolev escape-probability can be used when (1)\SpecialChar ~
a large velocity
 gradient is present in the gas flow, and (2)\SpecialChar ~
the intrinsic line width is
 negligible compared to the Doppler broadening of the line.
 In our earlier models (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{harries:2000}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

), this method was used to compute the line profiles since the condition
 (1) and (2) are reasonably satisfied.
 However, as noted and demonstrated by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

, even with a moderate amount of mass-accretion rate (
\begin_inset Formula $~10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

), Stark broadening becomes important in the optically thick H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 line.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

 also pointed out that the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles from CTTS typically have the wings extending to 
\begin_inset Formula $500\,\mathrm{km\, s^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

(e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
cite{edwards:1994}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

) which cannot be explained by the infall velocity of the gas along the
 magnetosphere alone.
 
