To implement the broadening mechanism, two modifications to our previous
 model (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

) are necessary as similarly done by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

.
 First, the emission and absorption profiles must be replaced by a Voigt
 profile which is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H\left(a,y\right)\equiv\frac{a}{\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-y'^{2}}}{\left(y-y'\right)^{2}+a^{2}}\, dy'\label{eq:voigt_profile_def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\Gamma/4\pi\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\left(\nu-\nu_{0}\right)/\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'=\left(\nu'-\nu_{0}\right)/\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset 

 (c.f.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{mihalas:1978}
\end_inset 

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is the line centre frequency, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset 

 is the Doppler line width of hydrogen atom (due to its thermal motion)
 which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}=\left(2kT/m_{\mathrm{H}}\right)^{1/2}\times\left(\nu_{0}/c\right)$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

 is the mass of a hydrogen atom.
 The damping constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset 

, which depends on the physical condition of the gas, is parameterised by
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet*{vernazza:1973}
\end_inset 

 as follows:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\Gamma & = & C_{\mathrm{rad}}+C_{\mathrm{vdW}}\left(\frac{n_{\mathrm{HI}}}{10^{16}\,\mathrm{cm^{-3}}}\right)\left(\frac{T}{5000\,\mathrm{K}}\right)^{0.3}\nonumber \\
 &  & +\, C_{\mathrm{Stark}}\left(\frac{n_{e}}{10^{12}\,\mathrm{cm^{-3}}}\right)^{2/3}\label{eq:dampimg_constant_def}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{H\, I}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{e}$
\end_inset 

 are the number density of neutral hydrogens and that of free electrons.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{rad}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{vdW}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{Stark}}$
\end_inset 

 are natural broadening, van der Waals broadening, and linear Stark broadening
 constants respectively.
 We simply adopt this parameterisation along with the values of broadening
 constants for H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 from 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{luttermoser:1992}
\end_inset 

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{rad}}=6.5\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{vdW}}=4.4\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{Stark}}=1.17\times10^{-3}$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

.
 In terms of level populations and the Voigt profile, the line opacity for
 the transition 
\begin_inset Formula $i\rightarrow j$
\end_inset 

 can be written as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\chi_{l}=\frac{\pi^{1/2}e^{2}}{m_{e}c}f_{ij}n_{j}\left(1-\frac{g_{j}n_{i}}{g_{i}n_{j}}\right)H\left(a,y\right)\label{eq:line_opacity}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}$
\end_inset 

 are the oscillator strength, the population of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

-th level, the population of 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

-th level, the degeneracy of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

-th level, and the degeneracy of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

-th level respectively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{e}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset 

 are the electron mass and charge (c.f.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{mihalas:1978}
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

The second modification in our model is the replacement of the method of
 solving the formal solution from the Monte Carlo radiative transfer method
 with Sobolev approximation to the direct integration method (c.f.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

).
 We specify the cylindrical coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p,\, q,\, t\right)$
\end_inset 

 which is the original stellar coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\rho,\,\phi,\, z\right)$
\end_inset 

 rotated (around 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset 

 axis) by the inclination of the line of sight, i.e.
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

-axis coincides with the line of sight.
 The observed flux (
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{\nu}=\frac{1}{4\pi d^{2}}\int_{0}^{p_{\mathrm{max}}}\int_{0}^{2\pi}p\,\sin q\, I_{\nu}\mathrm{\, d}q\,\mathrm{d}p\label{eq:flux_integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 are the distance to an observer, the maximum extent to the model space
 in the projected (rotated) plane, and the specific intensity (
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) in the direction on observer at the outer boundary.
 For a given ray along 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

, the specific intensity is given by:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
I_{\nu}=I_{0}e^{-\tau_{\infty}}+\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{\infty}}S_{\nu}\left(t\right)\, e^{-\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau\label{eq:formal_sol_integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 are the intensity at the boundary on the opposite to the observer and the
 source function (
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\nu}/\chi_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) of the stellar atmosphere/wind at a frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset 

.
 For a ray which intersects with the stellar core, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is computed from the stellar atmosphere mode of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{kurucz:1979}
\end_inset 

 as described in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Continuum-Source}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}=0$
\end_inset 

 otherwise.
 The initial position of each ray is assigned to be at the centre of the
 surface element (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}A=p\,\sin q\,\mathrm{d}q\,\mathrm{dp}$
\end_inset 

).
 The code execution time is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\, n_{q}\, n_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{q}$
\end_inset 

 are the number of cylindrical radial and angular points for the flux integratio
n, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

is the number of frequency points.
 In the models presented in the next (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Results}

\end_inset 

), 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=180$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{q}=100$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\nu}=101$
\end_inset 

 are used unless specified otherwise.
 The linearly spaced radial grid is used for the area where the ray intersects
 with magnetosphere, and the logarithmically spaced grid is used for the
 wind and the accretion disc regions.
\layout Standard

The optical depth 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 is equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formal_sol_integral}

\end_inset 

 is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tau\left(t\right)\equiv\int_{t}^{\infty}\chi_{\nu}\left(t'\right)\,\mathrm{d}t'\]

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 is the opacity of media the ray passes through.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

 is the total optical depth measured from the initial ray point to the observer
 (or to the outer boundary closer to the observer).
 Initially, the optical depth segments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d\tau}$
\end_inset 

 are computed at the intersections of a ray with the original AMR grid in
 which the opacity and emissivity information are stored.
 For high optical depth models, additional points are inserted between the
 original points along the ray, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 values are interpolated to those points to ensure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\tau<0.05$
\end_inset 

 for the all ray segments.
\layout Standard

For a point in the magnetosphere and the wind flows, the emissivity and
 the opacity of the media are given as:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\{ \begin{array}{rcl}
\eta_{\nu} & = & \eta_{\mathrm{c}}^{\mathrm{H}}+\eta_{l}^{\mathrm{H}}\\
\chi_{\nu} & = & \chi_{c}^{\mathrm{H}}+\chi_{l}^{\mathrm{H}}+\sigma_{\mathrm{es}}\end{array}\right.\label{eq:emiss_opa_gas}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mathrm{c}}^{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{l}^{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

 are the continuum and line emissivity of hydrogen.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{c}^{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{l}^{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{es}}$
\end_inset 

 are the continuum, line opacity (equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:line_opacity}

\end_inset 

) of hydrogen, and the electron scattering opacity.
 Similarly, for a point in the accretion disc,
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\{ \begin{array}{rcl}
\eta_{\nu} & = & 0\\
\chi_{\nu} & = & \kappa_{\mathrm{abs}}^{\mathrm{dust}}+\kappa_{\mathrm{sca}}^{\mathrm{dust}}\end{array}\right.\label{eq:emiss_opa_dust}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{\mathrm{abs}}^{\mathrm{dust}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{\mathrm{sca}}^{\mathrm{dust}}$
\end_inset 

