\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

 proposed the two-dimensional classification of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 emission profiles of T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars and Herbig Ae/Be stars.
 Their classification scheme contains four classes (I, II, III and IV) different
iated by the ratio of the secondary-to-primary emission components in the
 profiles.
 Each classes are divided into two sub-classes (B and R) which depends whether
 the absorption component is on the blue or red side.
 Readers are refereed to Fig.\SpecialChar ~
4 of their paper.
 Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_reipurth}

\end_inset 

 shows the sample model profiles which are classified according to the definitio
n of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

.
 The combination of the disc wind, magnetospherical accretion, and accretion
 disc can reasonably reproduce all the classes of the profiles seen in observati
ons.
 Similar profiles can be reproduced if the bipolar wind is used instead
 of the disc wind, but the wind absorption at a given velocity location
 occurs at a different inclination angles when the wind type is switched
 from the bipolar wind to the disc wind.
 The corresponding model parameters used to reproduce the profiles in the
 figure are given in Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:classification}

\end_inset 

 along with brief comments on possible physical conditions which leads to
 the profiles in each class.
 
\layout Standard

Using the samples of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 from 43 CTTS, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

 found the most common (33\SpecialChar ~
per\SpecialChar ~
cent) type of the profile is Type III-B.
 Interestingly, the most common profile type seen in the profiles from both
 the bipolar wind, disc and magnetosphere hybrid model (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

) and the disc-wind and the magnetosphere hybrid model (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

) are Type III-B profiles.
 In this type of profiles, the main emission comes from the magnetosphere,
 and the profile shape is altered a slightly blue-asymmetric one to a slightly
 red-asymmetric one via the wind absorption in the blue wing.
 The second most common profile (26\SpecialChar ~
per\SpecialChar ~
cent) 
\layout Standard

Type I (symmetric around line centres) is mainly produced in the magnetosphere.
 Although not shown here, this type of profile can be reproduced with the
 disc-wind, magnetosphere hybrid mode with pole on configuration.
 Since there is not material in the polar region in the disc wind model,
 the observer can look the magnetosphere almost directory for high inclination
 cases, provided that wind temperature is low enough so that the wind emission
 is negligible.
 Type II-R and Type II-B can be produced in a similar physical conditions
 (e.g.
 in a slow accretion and low temperature wind plus a magnetosphere).
 Main difference is between the two is in their inclination angles.
 The former is more likely seen with high inclination.
\layout Standard

Type III-R is the least common type of the observed profile (2\SpecialChar ~
per\SpecialChar ~
cent) according
 to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

.
 Incidentally, we also had a hard time to reproduce this type of profile
 since this can be achieve only at narrow range of parameter space (very
 high inclination angle with disc wind model, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}\sim8300\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}~10^{-8}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

Similarly the Type IV-R is the second least common type of observed profile
 (5\SpecialChar ~
per\SpecialChar ~
cent) which shows the inverse P-Cyg profile shape.
 This can be understood since the magnetospherical accretion model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

 predicts that the redshifted absorption can occur at a limited range of
 inclination angle with which the hot continuum flux from the footprint
 of the magnetosphere is seen through relatively fast moving gas in the
 accretion stream.
 Finally Type III-R profile is very similar to Type II-R, but the wind in
 this type of profile may be accretion faster than that in Type II-R.
\layout Standard


