As a demonstrative purpose, we present a model fit of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 observation of a classical T Tauri star (T\SpecialChar ~
Tau) obtained by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{vink:2005}
\end_inset 

.
 T\SpecialChar ~
Tau is known to be a triple system (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koresko:2000}
\end_inset 

).
 One of the star in the system T\SpecialChar ~
Tau\SpecialChar ~
N (a prototype for T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars) is dominatin
g in optical (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{calvet:1994}
\end_inset 

).
 The rotational velocity and the rotational period of the star found by
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{herbst:1987}
\end_inset 

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i=19.5\pm2.5\,\mathrm{km\, s^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2.80\,\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset 

 respectively.
 The inclination of the disc is known to be relatively small (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $i=29^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{akeson:2002}
\end_inset 

).
 There is a rather large scatter in the previously estimated the accretion
 rates e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $3\times10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{johns-krull:2000}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3.1-5.7\right)\times10^{-8}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{calvet:2004}
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

For the photospheric model, the following parameters from 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{calvet:2004}
\end_inset 

 are adopted: 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{eff}}=5500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{*}=1.9\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{*}=2.9\, R_{*}$
\end_inset 

.
 The standard geometry for the magnetosphere (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mi}}=2.2\, R_{*}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mo}}=3.0\, R_{*}$
\end_inset 

) and the bipolar wind configuration (Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

) are used for simplicity.
 Again, our purpose here is not to obtain the best fit parameters, but rather
 it is to examine if the model is capable of reasonably reproducing the
 data from a real object, in this case, T\SpecialChar ~
Tau\SpecialChar ~
N.
 The main parameters here (1)\SpecialChar ~
the temperature of the magnetospherical accretion
 flow (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset 

), (2)\SpecialChar ~
the mass-accretion rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

), (3)\SpecialChar ~
the temperature of the wind (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

), and (4)\SpecialChar ~
the wind mass-loss rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M_{\mathrm{wind}}}$
\end_inset 

).
 The inclination angle is simplify adopted from 
\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
g
\backslash 
citealt{akeson:2002}
\end_inset 

 i.e.\SpecialChar ~

